3 Protocol

Traits:

  • project out covariates form traits (see below);
  • remove individuals, for whom any trait value is missing (so, there is complete overlap in terms of phenotyping).

SNPs:

  • take genotyped SNPs;
  • use QC following the Po-Rus pipeline;
  • filter out SNPs with MAF <1%.

Estimation of phenotypic correlations using LDSC:

  • compute LD-scores for our SNPs using 1,000 Genomes reference panel of EUR;
    • unexpectedly, there are only approx. 100,000/600,000 HapMap 3 SNPs;
  • run bi-variate LDSC to estimate \(\rho\) parameter;
  • run uni-variate LDSC to asses the population stratification.

GWAS:

  • run PLINK 1.9 for single-trait GWAS
  • run plink.multivariate for CCA-based multi-trait GWAS;
  • run cusom R code (see below) for JASS.

By looking at the last plot, weve decided to exclude Height from the multi-trait analysis.

Also, there is a systematic upward bias in estimation of \(\rho\) by LDSC.

body_HEIGHTz_orth 0.4881 (0.0235) 1.8809 3.4525 1.2858 (0.0214) 0.1165 (0.0087)
body_HIP_orth 0.2111 (0.0099) 1.5585 1.9597 1.0888 (0.0104) 0.0926 (0.0109)
body_WAIST_orth 0.1926 (0.0076) 1.529 1.8027 1.0899 (0.0097) 0.112 (0.0121)
body_WEIGHT_orth 0.2532 (0.0109) 1.6448 2.1665 1.1204 (0.0118) 0.1032 (0.0101)
body_WHR_orth 0.1554 (0.0062) 1.453 1.7059 1.0884 (0.0095) 0.1252 (0.0134)

https://github.com/bulik/ldsc/wiki/Heritability-and-Genetic-Correlation:

Lambda GC is median(chi^2)/0.4549. Mean chi^2 is the mean chi-square statistic. Intercept is the LD Score regression intercept. The intercept should be close to 1, unless the data have been GC corrected, in which case it will often be lower. Ratio is (intercept-1)/(mean(chi^2)-1), which measures the proportion of the inflation in the mean chi^2 that the LD Score regression intercept ascribes to causes other than polygenic heritability. The value of ratio should be close to zero, though in practice values of 10-20% are not uncommon, probably due to sample/reference LD Score mismatch or model misspecification (e.g., low LD variants have slightly higher h^2 per SNP)

3.2.2 A special case of GWAS on Height

https://www.cell.com/cms/attachment/2107562562/2082039991/mmc1.pdf?code=cell-site (page 6):

But in the case of height there are two key issues: (1) essentially all of the genome is associated with height, and (2) selection on height has likely played a causal role in driving allele frequency differentiation across Europe. Thus if we correct for structure aggressively we are actually likely to remove real signal. We suspect that current methods may over-correct for structure for other highly polygenic traits as well, although the bias should be less severe in most other cases

4.2 R code to compute JASS (Omnibus)

Input:

  • a matrix Z of single-trait Z-scores with SNPs in rows and Z-scores in columns;
  • a covariance matrix among Z-scores (in practice, estimated by LDSC as phenotypic correlations)
ukbjass_omnibus <- function(Z, Sigma)
{
  ### check
  stopifnot(all(colnames(Z) == rownames(Sigma)))
  stopifnot(all(colnames(Z) == colnames(Sigma)))
  
  ### Omnibus test
  Sigma_inv <- solve(Sigma)
      
  P1 <- tcrossprod(Z, Sigma_inv)
  P2 <- P1 * Z # element-wise multiplication
  Z2 <- rowSums(P2)
  
  pval <- pchisq(Z2, df = ncol(Z), lower = FALSE)
}
